# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sqlalchemy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] In software engineering, the **data mapper pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Create, Read, Update, and Delete, that operate on objects that represent domain entity types in a data store.
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] A Data Mapper is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] The goal of the pattern is to keep the in-memory representation and the persistent data store independent of each other and the data mapper itself.
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] This is useful when one needs to model and enforce strict business processes on the data in the domain layer that do not map neatly to the persistent data store.
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] The layer is composed of one or more mappers (or Data Access Objects), performing the data transfer.
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] Generic mappers will handle many different domain entity types; dedicated mappers will handle one or a few.
[src:sqlalchemy/data-mapper-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:sqlalchemy/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] For new users who want to quickly see what basic ORM use looks like, here’s an abbreviated form of the mappings and examples used in the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The code here is fully runnable from a clean command line.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] As the descriptions in this section are intentionally **very short**, please proceed to the full SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial for a much more in-depth description of each of the concepts being illustrated here.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Changed in version 2.0: The ORM Quickstart is updated for the latest **PEP 484**-aware features using new constructs including `mapped_column()`.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] See the section ORM Declarative Models for migration information.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Here, we define module-level constructs that will form the structures which we will be querying from the database.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The mapping starts with a base class, which above is called `Base`, and is created by making a simple subclass against the `DeclarativeBase` class.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Individual mapped classes are then created by making subclasses of `Base`.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] A mapped class typically refers to a single particular database table, the name of which is indicated by using the `__tablename__` class-level attribute.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Next, columns that are part of the table are declared, by adding attributes that include a special typing annotation called `Mapped`.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The name of each attribute corresponds to the column that is to be part of the database table.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The datatype of each column is taken first from the Python datatype that’s associated with each `Mapped` annotation; `int` for `INTEGER`, `str` for `VARCHAR`, etc.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Nullability derives from whether or not the `Optional[]` (or its equivalent) type modifier is used.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] More specific typing information may be indicated using SQLAlchemy type objects in the right side `mapped_column()` directive, such as the `String` datatype used above in the `User.name` column.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The association between Python types and SQL types can be customized using the type annotation map.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `mapped_column()` directive is used for all column-based attributes that require more specific customization.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Besides typing information, this directive accepts a wide variety of arguments that indicate specific details about a database column, including server defaults and constraint information, such as membership within the primary key and foreign keys.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `mapped_column()` directive accepts a superset of arguments that are accepted by the SQLAlchemy `Column` class, which is used by SQLAlchemy Core to represent database columns.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] All ORM mapped classes require at least one column be declared as part of the primary key, typically by using the `Column.primary_key` parameter on those `mapped_column()` objects that should be part of the key.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] In the above example, the `User.id` and `Address.id` columns are marked as primary key.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Taken together, the combination of a string table name as well as a list of column declarations is known in SQLAlchemy as table metadata.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Setting up table metadata using both Core and ORM approaches is introduced in the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial at Working with Database Metadata.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The above mapping is an example of what’s known as Annotated Declarative Table configuration.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Other variants of `Mapped` are available, most commonly the `relationship()` construct indicated above.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] In contrast to the column-based attributes, `relationship()` denotes a linkage between two ORM classes.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] In the above example, `User.addresses` links `User` to `Address`, and `Address.user` links `Address` to `User`.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `relationship()` construct is introduced in the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial at Working with ORM Related Objects.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Finally, the above example classes include a `__repr__()` method, which is not required but is useful for debugging.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Mapped classes can be created with methods such as `__repr__()` generated automatically, using dataclasses.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] More on dataclass mapping at Declarative Dataclass Mapping.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `Engine` is a **factory** that can create new database connections for us, which also holds onto connections inside of a Connection Pool for fast reuse.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `echo=True` parameter indicates that SQL emitted by connections will be logged to standard out.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] A full intro to the `Engine` starts at Establishing Connectivity - the Engine.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] A lot just happened from that bit of Python code we wrote.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] For a complete overview of what’s going on on with Table metadata, proceed in the Tutorial at Working with Database Metadata.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] We are now ready to insert data in the database.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] We accomplish this by creating instances of `User` and `Address` classes, which have an `__init__()` method already as established automatically by the declarative mapping process.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] We then pass them to the database using an object called a Session, which makes use of the `Engine` to interact with the database.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] It’s recommended that the `Session` be used in context manager style as above, that is, using the Python `with:` statement.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `Session` object represents active database resources so it’s good to make sure it’s closed out when a series of operations are completed.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] In the next section, we’ll keep a `Session` opened just for illustration purposes.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Basics on creating a `Session` are at Executing with an ORM Session and more at Basics of Using a Session.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Then, some varieties of basic persistence operations are introduced at Inserting Rows using the ORM Unit of Work pattern.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] With some rows in the database, here’s the simplest form of emitting a SELECT statement to load some objects.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] To create SELECT statements, we use the `select()` function to create a new `Select` object, which we then invoke using a `Session`.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The above query also made use of the `Select.where()` method to add WHERE criteria, and also used the `ColumnOperators.in_()` method that’s part of all SQLAlchemy column-like constructs to use the SQL IN operator.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] More detail on how to select objects and individual columns is at Selecting ORM Entities and Columns.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] It’s very common to query amongst multiple tables at once, and in SQL the JOIN keyword is the primary way this happens.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The above query illustrates multiple WHERE criteria which are automatically chained together using AND, as well as how to use SQLAlchemy column-like objects to create “equality” comparisons, which uses the overridden Python method `ColumnOperators.__eq__()` to produce a SQL criteria object.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Some more background on the concepts above are at The WHERE clause and Explicit FROM clauses and JOINs.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `Session` object, in conjunction with our ORM-mapped classes `User` and `Address`, automatically track changes to the objects as they are made, which result in SQL statements that will be emitted the next time the `Session` flushes.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Notice when we accessed `patrick.addresses`, a SELECT was emitted.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Background on different ways to access related items using more or less SQL is introduced at Loader Strategies.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] A detailed walkthrough on ORM data manipulation starts at Data Manipulation with the ORM.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] All things must come to an end, as is the case for some of our database rows - here’s a quick demonstration of two different forms of deletion, both of which are important based on the specific use case.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] First we will remove one of the `Address` objects from the “sandy” user.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] When the `Session` next flushes, this will result in the row being deleted.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] This behavior is something that we configured in our mapping called the delete cascade.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The last SELECT above was the lazy load operation proceeding so that the `sandy.addresses` collection could be loaded, so that we could remove the `sandy_address` member.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] There are other ways to go about this series of operations that won’t emit as much SQL.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Next, we will delete the “patrick” user entirely.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] For a top-level delete of an object by itself, we use the `Session.delete()` method; this method doesn’t actually perform the deletion, but sets up the object to be deleted on the next flush.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The `Session.delete()` method in this particular case emitted two SELECT statements, even though it didn’t emit a DELETE, which might seem surprising.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] This is because when the method went to inspect the object, it turns out the `patrick` object was expired, which happened when we last called upon `Session.commit()`, and the SQL emitted was to re-load the rows from the new transaction.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] This expiration is optional, and in normal use we will often be turning it off for situations where it doesn’t apply well.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] The Tutorial discusses ORM deletion at Deleting ORM Objects using the Unit of Work pattern.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] Background on object expiration is at Expiring / Refreshing; cascades are discussed in depth at Cascades.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] For a new user, the above sections were likely a whirlwind tour.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] There’s a lot of important concepts in each step above that weren’t covered.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] With a quick overview of what things look like, it’s recommended to work through the SQLAlchemy Unified Tutorial to gain a solid working knowledge of what’s really going on above.
[src:sqlalchemy/quickstart] 2007-2026, the SQLAlchemy authors and contributors.
[src:sqlalchemy/sqlalchemy] SQLAlchemy offers tools for database schema generation, querying, and object-relational mapping.
[src:sqlalchemy/sqlalchemy] SQLAlchemy was first released in February 2006.
[src:sqlalchemy/sqlalchemy] It has evolved to include a wide range of features for database interaction and has gained popularity among Python developers.
[src:sqlalchemy/sqlalchemy] The following example represents an n-to-1 relationship between movies and their directors.
[src:sqlalchemy/sqlalchemy] It is shown how user-defined Python classes create corresponding database tables, how instances with relationships are created from either side of the relationship, and finally how the data can be queried — illustrating automatically generated SQL queries for both lazy and eager loading.
